<DOC><DOCNO> AP880912-0227 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 0735EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   09-12 0516</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add ,0540</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal savings institution regulatorsannounced another in a series of large rescue packages, providing$557 million in aid to a Michigan home-building company to acquirefour insolvent Texas savings and loans.   Bank Board Chairman M. Danny Wall said Friday that the FederalSavings and Loan Insurance Corp. will provide $312 million inpromissory notes and $245 million in additional cash assistance andguarantees over the next 10 years.   Pulte Diversified Companies Inc., the acquiring company, isputting up $45 million for an 80 percent stake in the four thrifts,all in the Houston area, and for a fifth institution which was notidentified.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Window service at the nation's post offices,cut last February to save money, was restored starting lastSaturday.   While the postal window hours will be restored, the new hourswill not necessarily be the same as those that were in effect ateach office before the closings were imposed, officials said Friday.   Most post offices cut hours by about a half-day a week to helpcope with $160 million in congressionally imposed spending cuts.</TEXT><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Carlton Communications PLC of Britain said ithas agreed to buy Technicolor Inc., a U.S. film duplicating companywhose trademark appears on many top movies, for $780 million.   Carlton said Friday it will buy Technicolor, which also has apresence in the booming videocassette duplication market, from acompany controlled by Revlon Group Inc. Chairman Ronald Perelman.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Soviet Union has bought an additional350,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for delivery in the coming year,the Agriculture Department said.   The sale announced Friday brought total corn sold to the Sovietsin the last nine days for delivery in the 1988-89 year that startedSept. 1 to more than 2.6 million tons.   The latest sale could have a farm value of around $38 million.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co. said progressis being made toward ending a bitter dispute over control of Unix,the base computer software that has pitted it against such rivalsas IBM and Digital Equipment Corp.   ``We're still in negotiations'' with the Open SoftwareFoundation, which was formed by IBM, Digital, Hewlett-Packard Co.and others to create a version of Unix that would not be underATandamp;T's control, ATandamp;T spokesman John Skalko said Friday.   Unix, invented by ATandamp;T, has become popular with other computermakers because it allows programs to run on a wide variety ofcomputers without alteration. However, the software has splinteredinto many versions.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices took a zigzag path Friday, winding up with a modestgain in continued sluggish trading. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials rose 5.69 points to 2,068.61.   The dollar was mixed against key currencies as gold pricesplunged in U.S. trading.   Bond prices finished higher in volatile trading, pushing keyinterest rates below 9 percent.   Crude oil futures plunged amid rumors Saudi Arabia vetoedproposals for a special meeting of OPEC's pricing committee.</TEXT></DOC>